    "divine_council_note": "1 Enoch 58 presents the ultimate realization of humanity's divine council vocation. Created to be God's image-bearers and vice-regents (Genesis 1:26-28), humanity was always meant to participate in the heavenly administration. The Fall disrupted this, but did not cancel the plan. The resurrection transformation described here is humanity 2.0—not merely restored to Adamic glory, but elevated beyond it. [B] The righteous become 'companions of the heavenly host,' joining the b'nei elohim in worship and governance. This is not deification (they remain creatures), but it is glorification—a sharing in the divine nature (2 Peter 1:4). The divine council, which witnessed humanity's creation (Genesis 1:26) and fall (Genesis 3:22), now witnesses their restoration and exaltation. [A] Jesus confirms this: 'In the resurrection they neither marry nor are given in marriage, but are like angels in heaven' (Matthew 22:30).",
    
    "sections": [
        {
            "heading": "The Light of the Sun and Eternal Life (58:1-4)",
            "body": "[C] Enoch begins with a promise of illumination: the righteous will dwell 'in the light of the sun' and the elect 'in the light of eternal life.' This is not metaphorical—the text describes a literal, visible transformation. [A] Daniel 12:3 provides the canonical anchor: 'Those who are wise shall shine like the brightness of the sky above.' [B] The 'light of eternal life' is qualitatively different from solar light—it is the uncreated light of God's presence, the same light that existed before the sun (Genesis 1:3). <strong>The days of their life will have no end</strong>—this is not Greek immortality of the soul, but Hebrew resurrection of the body into an imperishable state. [C] 4Q521 (Messianic Apocalypse) from Qumran similarly speaks of God glorifying 'the pious on the throne of the eternal Kingdom,' connecting glorification with enthronement—a divine council image. The transformation is not escape from physicality but its perfection."
        },
        {
            "heading": "Garments of Glory and Life (58:3)",
            "body": "[C] The 'garments of glory' and 'garments of life' are a key Second Temple motif. In Jubilees 3:26-27, Adam and Eve are clothed in 'garments of glory' in Eden, which they lose at the Fall and are replaced with garments of skin. [B] The resurrection is thus a re-robing—the recovery of what was lost plus more. [A] Paul uses clothing metaphors for resurrection: 'we shall all be changed' (1 Corinthians 15:51), and 'we long to put on our heavenly dwelling' (2 Corinthians 5:2). [C] The Qumran Hodayot (1QHa) repeatedly thank God for 'clothing me with garments of splendor' and placing the speaker 'in the council of the Holy Ones' (1QHa 11:19-23). This was understood both as a present spiritual reality for the Qumran community and a future physical reality at the resurrection. <strong>The garments are not external adornments but the transformed body itself</strong>—a new mode of physical existence suited for the age to come."
        },
        {
            "heading": "Companions of the Heavenly Host (58:4-6)",
            "body": "[B] The righteous will 'become companions of the heavenly host' and 'partners with the angels.' This is the fulfillment of humanity's original vocation. [A] Psalm 8:5 declares that humans were made 'a little lower than elohim' (often translated 'angels' but the Hebrew is ambiguous—'gods/divine beings'). The resurrection closes that gap. [A] Hebrews 2:5-9 quotes Psalm 8 and applies it to Jesus, noting that 'we do not yet see everything in subjection to him,' but through Jesus' death and resurrection, humanity's destiny is secured. [C] 4Q418 (Instruction) from Qumran promises the wise that 'with the Sons of Heaven He has cast your lot'—the righteous are already, in some sense, members of the divine council, and this will be fully realized at the resurrection. [B] This is not pantheism or polytheism—the righteous remain creatures, but they are adopted into the family of God (Romans 8:14-17, Galatians 4:5-7). The divine council is not a pantheon of independent deities but the household of YHWH, and humans are brought into that household as sons and daughters."
        },
        {
            "heading": "The Reversal of Fortunes — From Suffering to Glory (58:5-6)",
            "body": "[A] The chapter emphasizes the <strong>great reversal</strong>: those who suffered on earth will inherit glory; those who oppressed them will face judgment. This is the Beatitudes before the Beatitudes. [A] Jesus: 'Blessed are those who are persecuted for righteousness' sake, for theirs is the kingdom of heaven' (Matthew 5:10). [A] Paul: 'I consider that the sufferings of this present time are not worth comparing with the glory that is to be revealed to us' (Romans 8:18). [C] 1 Enoch 58 specifies that the mighty who 'did not acknowledge whence their kingdom and glory came' will be judged. This is a critique of imperial power—earthly kingdoms derive their authority from God (Daniel 4:17, Romans 13:1), and when they deny this, they become demonic parodies of divine rule. [B] The Enochic tradition sees earthly empires as influenced by rebellious divine council members (the 'princes' of Daniel 10), and their fall is part of the cosmic reclamation project. The righteous, by contrast, acknowledge God as the source of all authority and thus inherit true kingship in the age to come."
        },
        {
            "heading": "Theological Implications — The Destiny of Humanity",
            "body": "[B] 1 Enoch 58 presents a <strong>maximalist anthropology</strong>—humanity's destiny is not mere survival or even bliss, but glorification and co-regency with God. This is the biblical vision from Genesis to Revelation: humans as image-bearers (Genesis 1:26), priests and kings (Exodus 19:6, Revelation 5:10), heirs of God and co-heirs with Christ (Romans 8:17). [A] The New Testament consistently affirms this: believers will 'judge angels' (1 Corinthians 6:3), 'reign on the earth' (Revelation 5:10), and be 'conformed to the image of [God's] Son' (Romans 8:29). [C] The Enochic tradition develops what is implicit in the Hebrew Bible and made explicit in the New Testament. [B] This is not works-righteousness—the transformation is a gift of grace—but neither is it cheap grace. The righteous are those who 'feared God and did not forget His commandments' (1 Enoch 58:5). <strong>Obedience is the evidence of faith, and glorification is the reward of faithfulness.</strong> [A] Paul: 'If we endure, we will also reign with him' (2 Timothy 2:12)."
        },
        {
            "heading": "New Testament Fulfillment — Christ as the Firstfruits",
            "body": "[A] The transformation described in 1 Enoch 58 is realized in Jesus' resurrection and transfiguration. At the Transfiguration (Matthew 17:1-8), Jesus' face shone like the sun and his clothes became white as light—a preview of the glorified state. [A] After the resurrection, Jesus appears in a body that is both physical (he eats fish, bears the scars of crucifixion) and transformed (he passes through locked doors, appears and disappears). [A] Paul calls Christ 'the firstfruits of those who have fallen asleep' (1 Corinthians 15:20)—his resurrection is the prototype and guarantee of ours. [A] 1 John 3:2: 'We shall be like him, because we shall see him as he is.' The beatific vision is not disembodied contemplation but transformative encounter—seeing God face to face changes us into his likeness. [B] This is the ultimate fulfillment of the divine council vision: humanity, represented by the incarnate Son, takes its seat at the right hand of the Father (Hebrews 1:3), and believers are seated with him 'in the heavenly places' (Ephesians 2:6). <strong>The Enochic hope is the Christian hope: resurrection, transformation, glorification, and eternal fellowship with God and his heavenly host.</strong>"
